		<h2>WIDENING ACCESS</h2><p>The Glasgow School of Art is committed to widening access to higher education and seeks to ensure equality of opportunity for all applicants.  We believe access to a world-class education in art, design and architecture should be open to all based on talent, ability and potential.</p><h2>INITIATIVES TO WIDEN PARTICIPATION AT THE GSA</h2><p>The GSA is involved in a number of initiatives to widening participation and is an active member of GOALS - a collaboration initiative of the Universities of Glasgow, Strathclyde, Paisley and Glasgow Caledonian, the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama and the GSA.  </p><p>GOALS aims to raise aspirations by introducing the idea of Higher Education to primary and secondary pupils who might not otherwise have thought that higher education was for them.  The GSA has a number of GOALS projects including:</p><ul><li>GOALS Portfolio Preparation in Schools project</li><li>GOALS Artists and Designers in Education programme</li><li>Campus Days for GOALS secondary schools</li></ul><p>The GSA is also manages on behalf of GOALS the REMIT project (Recruitment of Ethnic Minorities Into Teaching) to enhance and encourage participation in the teaching profession in primary, secondary and further education from the black and minority ethnic community in the West of Scotland. </p><p>We also have a number of non GOALS projects including:</p><ul><li>Clydesdale Bank Art for All</li></ul><p>Find out more about our projects using the links on the left.</p><h2>NEW INITIATIVES</h2><p><b>International Exchange</b></p><p>At the GSA we have developed one of the first international widening access programmes of its kind in higher education, in partnership with staff from Monash University Centre in Prato, Italy. </p><p>GSA students participating in the programme are young, first year undergraduate students from secondary schools across the West of Scotland characterised by low participation rates in higher education.  For two weeks they study the development of Italian art and design alongside Monash University students.  The lectures provide an art history and theory basis for on-site visits to museums, galleries and architectural sites in Prato (a leading European textiles centre) and in neighbouring locations including Florence, Pisa, Siena, Pistoia, Lucca and Arezzo. </p><p>The GSA intends to develop this project as part of its strategy for retention of non-traditional or under-represented groups whose experience of foreign travel and cultural visits is often limited.</p><p>If you would like to support this project through a donation or to support the creation of scholarships and travel bursaries, please visit the <a href="gsa.cfm?pid=549" target="new window">Alumni and Supporters</a> section of this website.</p><p><b>Further Education</b></p><p>GSA's relationship with Further Education Colleges delivering Art and Design courses is being systematically explored by Wider Access staff with a view to formally proposing a way forward in collaboration with specified FE colleges. We are exploring ways in which we could facilitate student transition from FE to GSA in the areas of Fine Art and Design at the appropriate level. </p><p>For more information on the GSA's widening participation activities, please contact Wider Access  Officer on +44 (0) 141 353 4569 or <a href="mailto:info@gsa.ac.uk" target="">info@gsa.ac.uk</a></p>
	

	

	

	

	

	

	
	
	
	
	


	
	







